### Update tracking details (FBM only)
To allow shipment tracking, you need to provide the `courier` and `tracking_code` for each order shipment.

> <i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
> This endpoint is available only for FBM (Fulfilled By Merchant) orders
>
> <i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
>The existing API endpoint is limited to updating tracking details only for orders shipped to customers and does not currently support return orders.
>These should be still handled through merchants panel for the time being.

<pre class="terminal">
  POST /merchants/ecommerce/orders/:code/tracking_details
</pre>


<%= render_recording :merchants_ecommerce_orders_tracking_details %>

<pre class="terminal">
curl -X POST https://api.skroutz.gr/merchants/ecommerce/orders/191128-1234567/tracking_details \
  -H 'Accept: application/vnd.skroutz+json; version=3.0' \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8' \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer your_access_token_here' \
  -d '{ "tracking_details": [ { "courier":"acs", "tracking_code":"224085551" } ] }'
</pre>


## Error handling

In case of errors, the response will have a representative HTTP status code
in the `4xx` or `5xx` range. The body would contain an array of `errors`.

For example, if you try to accept an order that is already accepted, you will
get a `422` HTTP status code (Unprocessable Entity), with the following body:

<%= render_code '{
  "errors": [
      {
          "code": "order_status",
          "messages": [
              "Order already accepted."
          ]
      }
  ]
}', 'javascript' %>

And if you try to reject an order that is already rejected, you will
also get a `422` HTTP status code (Unprocessable Entity), with the following body:

<%= render_code '{
  "errors": [
      {
          "code": "order_status",
          "messages": [
              "Order already rejected."
          ]
      }
  ]
}', 'javascript' %>

## Set as Ready integration flow

This section describes the recommended integration flow for shops enrolled in the
"Set as Ready" program. Read this before testing with the [sandbox](#test-requests-sandbox).

### Updated order response fields

The order response includes two new fields related to Set as Ready:

| Field | Type | Description |
| ----- | ---- | ----------- |
| `set_as_ready_required` | Boolean | `true` if the shop requires explicit set-as-ready (voucher download does not auto-mark as ready). `false` for shops with default behavior. |
| `is_ready_for_dispatch` | Boolean | `true` if the order has been marked as ready for dispatch. `false` otherwise. |

#### Example: enrolled shop, order not yet ready

~~~ json
{
  "order": {
    "code": "260225-123456",
    "state": "accepted",
    "set_as_ready_required": true,
    "is_ready_for_dispatch": false,
    "courier": "Skroutz Last Mile",
    "courier_voucher": "https://b.scdn.gr/path-to/voucher.pdf",
    "pickup_window": {
      "from": "2026-02-27T09:00:00+02:00",
      "to": "2026-02-27T12:00:00+02:00"
    }
  }
}
~~~

#### Example: enrolled shop, order marked as ready

~~~ json
{
  "order": {
    "code": "260225-123456",
    "state": "accepted",
    "set_as_ready_required": true,
    "is_ready_for_dispatch": true,
    "courier": "Skroutz Last Mile",
    "courier_voucher": "https://b.scdn.gr/path-to/voucher.pdf",
    "pickup_window": {
      "from": "2026-02-26T15:00:00+02:00",
      "to": "2026-02-26T18:00:00+02:00"
    }
  }
}
~~~

> In the example above, the `pickup_window` changed because the early set-as-ready
> triggered an auto-reschedule to an earlier date.

### For shops with `set_as_ready_required: true`

<pre>
1. Receive order (webhook or polling)
2. Accept order        → POST /merchants/ecommerce/orders/:code/accept
3. Download voucher    → GET  &lt;courier_voucher URL from order response&gt;
4. Prepare the package
5. Mark as ready       → POST /merchants/ecommerce/orders/:code/set_as_ready
6. Courier picks up
</pre>

> <i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
> Steps 3 and 5 are now independent. You can download the voucher at any time,
> but the courier will only schedule a pickup after step 5.

### For shops with `set_as_ready_required: false` (default)

No changes needed. The existing flow continues to work:

<pre>
1. Receive order
2. Accept order        → POST /merchants/ecommerce/orders/:code/accept
3. Download voucher    → GET  &lt;courier_voucher URL from order response&gt;
                         (auto-marks as ready)
4. Courier picks up
</pre>

### Tips for faster pickups

* Mark orders as ready as soon as they are physically prepared — don't wait for the pickup day
* If you mark as ready before 21:00 the day before the scheduled pickup, the system may reschedule to an earlier pickup window
* The earlier you mark as ready, the more likely an earlier pickup slot is available

### FAQ

**Q: What happens if I don't call `set_as_ready`?**
A: The courier will skip your stop. The order will not be picked up.

**Q: Can I still download the voucher without calling `set_as_ready`?**
A: Yes. Voucher download and set-as-ready are independent actions.

**Q: What happens if I call `set_as_not_ready`?**
A: The order is no longer considered ready. The system will attempt to move the pickup back to the
original scheduled date. If that's no longer possible (e.g., the date has passed), the current
pickup schedule remains.

**Q: Does this affect orders shipped with couriers other than Skroutz Last Mile?**
A: No. This only applies to orders shipped via Skroutz Last Mile (SLM).

